english:
  title: Record of the Reconstruction of the Pagoda at Yeonboksa Temple
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Way of Buddha takes compassion and generosity as virtue, and the unerring law of karma as its proof. Its teachings are vast and boundless, translated and transmitted to the Middle Kingdom, spreading to all four seas, enduring through a thousand ages, growing ever more flourishing as the years pass. From the highest nobles and ministers down to the common folk, all seek blessings and prosperity, and none fail to revere and believe. Temples and pagodas rise like peaks throughout the land, their numbers filling all beneath heaven. In our Eastern realm, since the declining years of Silla, the veneration of Buddha has been especially reverent. Within the capital, monasteries outnumber dwellings, and their grandest structures still stand today, testifying to the fervent devotion of that age.

    When Wang's dynasty unified the realm at its inception, it continued these practices without change, hoping for divine protection, establishing temples throughout the land—such is the way of support. Yeonboksa stands at the very heart of the capital's marketplace. Its original name was Tangsa, the Temple of Tang. In the local speech, Tang and Great are similar in sound, and thus it is also called Daesa, the Great Temple. Its halls are immense, numbering more than a thousand chambers. Within it are carved three ponds and nine wells, and to its south rises a five-tiered pagoda, aligned with the principles of wind and water—all documented in ancient texts, which I shall not here repeat.

    During Wang's five hundred years of rule, the realm suffered many upheavals, and the temple's fortunes rose and fell repeatedly. When the pagoda crumbled, none could say precisely when. In the reign of King Gongmin, efforts to rebuild began but remained unfinished. Later, a certain mad monk named Jang Won-shim, through connections with the powerful, troubled the people and felled timber, yet his work too came to naught. King Gongyangyang, with the aid of generals and ministers, restored the dynasty's succession, and from his enthronement he devoted himself ever more to the Buddha's teachings. He commanded the monk Cheon-gyul and others to gather workers and begin the great work. In the second month of Sinmi, the old foundations were cleared and filled with wood and stone to strengthen them. By winter, six bays were erected both lengthwise and crosswise, grand and ample. Layer upon layer rose until five tiers were complete, crowned with flat stone. As completion drew near, a minister raised objections, causing work to halt. At that time, our Lord and Master, standing at the head of all officials, petitioned for the work's completion. Not long after, King Gongyangyang, having lost the Way, abdicated, and the Mandate of Heaven passed to His Majesty.

    I humbly reflect that His Majesty, possessed of divine martial virtue, has received the response of Heaven and men, ascended to the throne, and become the great guardian of the people and state. With supreme benevolence he cherishes all life; with great virtue he nurtures all things. Worthy sages apply their strength in service; the way of governance shines bright and flourishes. All former evils are reformed, all transformations are renewed. Every policy that enriches the nation and benefits the people is undertaken. Recognizing that the Buddha's teaching of compassionate love for all beings benefits the state, he upholds and does not abandon its practices. Thus he establishes grand designs and leaves enduring legacy for posterity—surely this is both magnificent and complete.

    With renewed diligence in superintending the work, the pagoda was finally brought to completion in the twelfth month of Renchen year. In the spring of Guiyou, the walls were painted in bright colors, the eaves seeming to fly above the clouds, birds soaring through heaven. Gold and jade gleam brilliantly, their radiance illuminating half the sky. Within the apex rests the Buddha's reliquary; in the middle chamber are stored the scriptures of the Great Canon; below is enshrined the image of Vairocana Buddha—all to bring blessing to the realm and eternal benefit to ten thousand generations. In the fourth month, a gathering for the Bodhisattva Manjushri was held to celebrate the completion. His Majesty commanded this servant Gwon Geun to record the particulars.

    This servant has heard that monks erect pagodas to manifest virtue, and the number of tiers reveals the height of that virtue. Five tiers and above constitute a true Buddhist pagoda. The teachings concerning merit and karmic consequence are exceedingly vast and profound, which is why from King Ashoka onward, successive rulers have honored and built them without ceasing. Yet when Bodhidharma answered Emperor Wu of Liang concerning the merit of building temples and pagodas, he said not a fragment of merit existed—for the Emperor expended wealth without cultivating the mind. In this case, however, no burden falls upon the common purse, no labor troubles the farmer. How then can the merit be easily reckoned? Since the merit is excellent, its reward shall naturally manifest. Heaven and humanity rejoice together; the visible and invisible worlds share in the blessing. May the benefits spread eternal and boundless, the good fortune endless and vast, the realm secure and the ages firm—this we may truly hope.

    This servant bows and presents these verses:

    The Buddha's teachings arose in the Western lands,
    Spread through all the world by translation into the tongue of Cathay.
    Its teachings of cause and effect are vast and profound,
    Above and below, none cease their fervent prayers for blessing.

    How towering and grand these temples and pagodas stand,
    Filling the six directions beneath heaven and earth.
    Silla revered them with utmost sincerity,
    The House of Wang upheld them, never changing course.

    Yeonboksa sits beside the marketplace,
    Within it three ponds carved, nine wells dug deep.
    To its south rose a five-tiered tower,
    Yet when it fell, none could mark the hour.

    Through many ages men sought to rebuild,
    Yet fate denied what their hands had willed.
    When heavenly fortune wanes, what can be done?
    Our sage lord bears virtue second to none.

    Heaven and humanity turn toward his rule,
    Accepting the mandate, his hand fate's tool.
    All transformation renewed, all corruption removed,
    Buddhism uplifted, the nation improved.

    The five-tiered pagoda rises anew, its work complete,
    No burden laid upon the farmers' weary feet.
    Soaring high like sacred Songak's peak,
    Its colors brilliant where clouds and temples speak.

    Above, the Buddha's relics shine with holy light,
    The vast Canon stored in chambers bright.
    Below, Vairocana's form in splendor dwells,
    Merit supreme and manifold blessings' swells.

    Our sage king ten thousand years shall reign,
    His fortune endless through ages' span.
    Let all beings taste compassion's gift,
    In merit's ocean forever drift.

    His Majesty commands this humble servant write,
    Yet crude and clumsy are these verses slight.
    I only pray this tower stands firm and tall,
    With the realm secure, through ages all.
  footnotes:
    - 'Yeonboksa (演福寺): A major Buddhist temple in the Korean capital, its name literally means ''Temple of Unfolding Fortune.'' The Korean text notes its original name was Tangsa (唐寺), from which ''Daesa'' (大寺, Great Temple) derives.'
    - 'Five-tiered pagoda: In Buddhist cosmology, five tiers typically represent the five elements or five celestial buddhas, making it an auspicious structure symbolizing Buddhist virtue.'
    - 'King Gongyangyang: The penultimate ruler of Goryeo dynasty (r. 1389-1392), whose abdication led to the establishment of the Joseon dynasty under Yi Seong-gye (the author''s contemporary ruler).'
    - 'Bodhidharma and Emperor Wu of Liang: A famous Zen dialogue in which Bodhidharma tells Emperor Wu that building temples without cultivating the mind produces no merit—the author uses this to contrast with the ''true'' merit of the Yeonboksa reconstruction.'
